<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="1145" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1145">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">814.00/12–944: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Long</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-09">December 9,
                                1944</date>.<lb/>[Received December 10—12:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>841. The Guatemalan Government has issued a decree convoking Presidential
                            elections December 17, 18 and 19, a further decree provides for election
                            of a Vice President and establishes qualifications for candidates for
                            President and Vice President with the provision that no member of the
                            Junta or their relatives or Cabinet members may be elected to either
                            position. Also the National Assembly has approved the convoking of a
                            Constitutional Assembly.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>